courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students will be able to:

1. explain how cultures function, and recognize the different perspectives that can be used to understand culture;
2. discuss how different cultures have both diverse and similar solutions to the problems of human existence;
3. analyze cultures and societies as informed through comparisons with other cultures and societies; and
4. explicate the connections among different subfields of social and cultural anthropology (which focus on different facets of culture, such as religion, gender, politics, economics, etc.) and how these facets are linked and integrated in each culture

By the end of this course, students will

1) understand how anthropology is practiced in its different areas and fields;
2) know the basics of how to write papers and how to most fruitfully proceed in their studies as anthropology students in the university;
3) know the department's different teachers and the different ways in which they envision anthropology; and

4) have a broad overall sense of what anthropology as a discipline consists of.

1) To learn field research techniques for ethnographic study;
2) To develop skills and knowledge in designing and carrying our research projects independently;
3) To enhance effective communication and writing abilities;
4) To be aware of ethical and personal issues of field research.

Students taking this course will:

learn to see the cultural nature of reality and of the supernatural;

understand how many apparently irrational and bizarre beliefs make sense in their cultural contexts;

learn how to use critical thinking while at the same time being tolerant of other views;

develop a healthy scientific skepticism, while at the same time remaining open to new ideas;

be able to analyze other cases that will emerge later in life.

Through taking this course, students will:

* understand how the treatment of death varies cross-culturally, and thus how our own personalunderstandings of death are not necessarily universally shared;
* analyze processes of grieving and structures of death ritual in terms of how they vary cross-culturally;
* apply theoretical schemes of cultural evolution to understandings of death over human history;
* evaluate how death and fear of death affects contemporary politics, economics, and culture in societies across the globe;
* evaluate the place of death within our own lives.

1. Understand how humans have engaged the environment historically and cross-culturally;

2. Examine the relationship between the environment, local communities and the state in the present world through issues including deforestation, climate change, and nuclear disaster;

3. Explore contemporary environmental crises to cultivate sensitivity to possible forms of resistance and action from local and global perspectives.

Students who have taken this course will:

* be able to see and understand the cultural and historical nature of sports;
* understand the roles that sports play in modern societies;
* know how to apply fieldwork methods to research a group’s sub-culture, including implicit and explicit rules;
* be able to analyze the elements of competition, cooperation, luck and skill, and other variables that make sports entertaining to play and watch and talk about;

be able to analyze and appreciate other sports that they will encounter later in life.

