courses.learning_outcomes:
After the completion of this course, students will:

1. Understand and appreciate the cultural dimensions of business operations and organization in different historical, political, and social settings;
2. Acquire the necessary ethnographic skills to study diverse aspects of business operations and organization;
3. Be able to rethink and challenge the existing assumptions regarding business practices in the modern world;
4. Gain the analytical tools to examine issues of over-consumption, over-production, dispossession, oppression, and other relevant discontent under global capitalism;
5. Be able to examine critically the role SDGs could play in addressing disparities and injustices in the world;
6. Understand the importance of building a more inclusive, equal and diverse society.

Upon completing this course, students will be able to:

1. analyze the globalization of culture, a process taking place across the world today and shaping all of our lives;
2. recognize different aspects of the globalization of culture, including those involving recent history, economics, consumption, mass media, migration, and cultural identity;
3. discuss the costs and benefits of contemporary processes of globalization to individuals, societies, and the world; and
4. evaluate the nature of your own culture and selves within a globalizing world.

1. to comprehend the complex meanings of violence within a web of power relations both historically and cross-culturally;

2. to analyze the ways current discourses of violence and human rights are specific to our historical moment;

3. to cultivate historical and cross-cultural sensitivity in understanding diverse human experiences, crucial to the facilitation of dialogues and collaboration in the advancement of transformative justice;

4. to understand critically the role SDGs could play in addressing global inequalities.

# 1 Understand what is “scientific reasoning”, and be able to evaluate claims about the past by combining anthropological knowledge and understanding of scientific techniques;

# 2 General understanding about the history of technology and basic knowledge background to appreciate technological achievements in the past;

# 3 Equip students with skills to conduct digital humanities research and foundation to develop cross-disciplinary study;

# 4 Inspire students of different backgrounds to employ new techniques addressing problems challenging most cultural heritage projects that our current society is encountering.

