courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completing this course, students will:
- -have a general understanding of the subdisciplines of anthropology;
- -know the key concepts of the field;
- -know the major theories that explain human cultural and societal diversity and complexity;
- -be able to use the discipline’s holistic approach to understand human societies and cultures.

This course is designed for students to:
1) learn anthropological perspectives on ethnicity;
2) reflect on their own ethnic identity (or the lack of it) and question their taken-for-granted assumptions regarding ethnicity;
3) allow themselves to apply what they learn in class in real life situations
4) obtain a perspective regarding the relations among politics, history, culture and peoplehood; and
5) have their own answers about what ethnicity is and related questions for further investigation.

Toward the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:
1) understand the basic concepts of gender and how gender is culturally constructed in particular societies;
2) be aware of how gender and sexuality work as guiding principles in daily lives;
3) apply social theories to explain gender phenomena of particular cultures, particularly of Asian societies.
4) be aware of the impact of globalization on women’s lives and experience;
5) analyze a range of gender issues from a global perspective.

Through taking this course, students will:

- -understand how the treatment of death varies cross-culturally, and thus how our own personal understandings of death are not necessarily universally shared;
- -understand processes of grieving and structures of death ritual cross-culturally;
- -acquire a broad sense of how understandings of death have shifted over human cultural evolution;
- -comprehend how death and fear of death affects contemporary politics, economics, and culture;
- -comprehend more deeply the place of death within our own lives

